export const questionBank3 = [
  // DOMAIN 1: Design Secure Architectures (~15 questions)
  {q:"A company is migrating a legacy application that uses a self-managed MySQL database with stored procedures and triggers. The application must maintain the same database engine, support cross-region disaster recovery with an RPO of less than 1 second, and minimize operational overhead. Which solution meets ALL requirements?", opts:["Amazon Aurora MySQL with Aurora Global Database","Amazon RDS MySQL with cross-region Read Replicas","Amazon RDS MySQL Multi-AZ with automated backups and cross-region snapshot copy","Self-managed MySQL on EC2 with synchronous replication across regions"], correct:0, exp:"Aurora Global Database supports MySQL compatibility (stored procedures/triggers work), provides <1 second RPO for cross-region DR, and is fully managed. RDS cross-region replicas have seconds of lag (RPO > 1s). Snapshot copies are even longer.", domain:1},
  {q:"A financial services company needs to process sensitive customer data. Regulations require that encryption keys must be stored in FIPS 140-2 Level 3 validated hardware, the company must have exclusive control over the keys, and all API calls to the key management system must be logged. Which combination of services satisfies these requirements?", opts:["AWS KMS with customer-managed CMKs and CloudTrail","AWS CloudHSM with CloudTrail logging","AWS KMS with custom key store backed by CloudHSM and CloudTrail","AWS Secrets Manager with KMS encryption and CloudTrail"], correct:2, exp:"KMS custom key store backed by CloudHSM provides FIPS 140-2 Level 3 compliance, exclusive key control (single-tenant HSM), AND deep AWS integration with CloudTrail logging of all API calls. CloudHSM alone lacks the integrated AWS service logging. Standard KMS is only FIPS 140-2 Level 2.", domain:1},
  {q:"An application running on EC2 in a private subnet needs to access an S3 bucket and a DynamoDB table. The security team requires that NO traffic traverses the public internet. The solution must also minimize costs. Which approach meets all requirements?", opts:["Deploy a NAT Gateway in the public subnet for internet access to AWS services","Create VPC Gateway Endpoints for both S3 and DynamoDB","Create a VPC Interface Endpoint (PrivateLink) for S3 and a Gateway Endpoint for DynamoDB","Set up AWS Direct Connect to reach AWS services privately"], correct:1, exp:"Gateway Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB are free (no hourly charge, no data processing charge) and keep traffic within the AWS network. Interface Endpoints cost ~$0.01/hr per AZ + data processing. NAT Gateway uses public internet. Direct Connect is expensive overkill.", domain:1},
  {q:"A solutions architect must design a multi-account strategy where development accounts can only launch t3.micro and t3.small instances, production accounts can use any instance type, and no account can disable CloudTrail. Which combination of AWS Organizations features achieves this with LEAST effort?", opts:["Create separate OUs for dev and prod, attach an SCP to the dev OU restricting instance types, and attach an SCP to the root denying cloudtrail:StopLogging","Create IAM policies in each dev account restricting instance types and enable CloudTrail in all accounts with an SCP preventing deletion","Use AWS Config rules to detect non-compliant instances and Lambda to terminate them, with an SCP for CloudTrail","Attach permission boundaries to all IAM roles in dev accounts and use an SCP at root for CloudTrail"], correct:0, exp:"SCPs at the OU level are the cleanest solution. Dev OU SCP restricts instance types. Root-level SCP preventing CloudTrail disable applies to ALL accounts including prod. IAM policies would need to be maintained per-account. Permission boundaries are per-role.", domain:1},
  {q:"A web application uses Amazon Cognito for authentication. The company wants to allow users to sign in with their corporate Active Directory credentials AND their social media accounts (Google, Facebook). The application must support MFA for corporate users only. What is the correct architecture?", opts:["Use Cognito User Pool with SAML federation for AD and social identity providers, configure MFA as required for the AD group","Use Cognito Identity Pool with AD Connector for corporate users and Cognito User Pool for social users","Create two separate Cognito User Pools - one for corporate (with MFA) and one for social - and federate both to an Identity Pool","Use Cognito User Pool with an AD Connector, social identity providers, and a pre-authentication Lambda trigger to enforce MFA conditionally"], correct:3, exp:"A single Cognito User Pool can federate both SAML (corporate AD via AD Connector) and social providers. A pre-authentication Lambda trigger can conditionally enforce MFA only for corporate users. Two User Pools creates management complexity. Cognito User Pool (not Identity Pool) handles authentication.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company stores sensitive documents in S3. They need to ensure that: (1) objects are encrypted with keys the company manages, (2) the encryption key is automatically rotated annually, (3) if a key is deleted, there is a recovery window, and (4) all key usage is audited. Which encryption approach satisfies ALL requirements?", opts:["SSE-S3 (AES-256) with S3 bucket policies","SSE-KMS with a customer-managed CMK, automatic rotation enabled, and CloudTrail logging","SSE-C with customer-provided keys rotated by an external HSM","Client-side encryption with KMS-managed data keys"], correct:1, exp:"SSE-KMS with customer-managed CMK satisfies all: company manages the key (CMK policies), automatic annual rotation is a single checkbox, CMKs have a 7-30 day waiting period before deletion (recovery window), and all key usage is logged in CloudTrail. SSE-S3 keys are AWS-managed. SSE-C requires you to manage rotation yourself with no recovery window.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company has an application that writes sensitive logs to CloudWatch Logs. A compliance requirement states that no employee, including administrators, should be able to delete or modify log data for 7 years. What is the MOST secure and cost-effective approach?", opts:["Enable CloudWatch Logs retention policy set to 7 years","Export logs to S3 with a Glacier Deep Archive lifecycle policy and S3 Object Lock in Compliance mode","Stream logs to Kinesis Firehose to S3 with versioning and an IAM policy denying deletions","Use CloudWatch Logs with resource-based policies denying all delete actions"], correct:1, exp:"S3 Object Lock in Compliance mode is the only option that truly prevents deletion by ANYONE (including root) for the retention period. Glacier Deep Archive is cheapest for 7-year retention. CloudWatch retention can be changed by admins. IAM policies can be modified by administrators.", domain:1},
  {q:"A solutions architect is designing a data lake on S3. Multiple teams need access to different datasets with different permission levels. Some datasets contain PII that must be masked for certain teams. The solution must centrally manage permissions without modifying bucket policies per team. Which service should be used?", opts:["S3 Access Points with different policies per team","AWS Lake Formation with column-level and row-level security","IAM policies with conditions based on S3 prefixes and tags","Amazon Macie integrated with IAM for dynamic access control"], correct:1, exp:"Lake Formation provides centralized fine-grained access control for data lakes including column-level security, row-level filtering, and cell-level masking for PII. It manages permissions centrally without per-bucket policies. S3 Access Points simplify access but can't do column/row-level security or PII masking.", domain:1},
  {q:"An application running on ECS Fargate needs to pull a Docker image from Amazon ECR and access secrets stored in Secrets Manager during startup. The task execution role has the appropriate IAM permissions, but tasks are failing with 'Access Denied' errors. Which combination of issues should the architect investigate? (Choose TWO that are most likely)", opts:["The VPC endpoints for ECR and Secrets Manager are not configured in the private subnet","The ECS task role (not execution role) needs ECR permissions","The security group on the Fargate task is blocking outbound HTTPS traffic","The ECR repository policy explicitly denies the task execution role"], correct:0, exp:"In private subnets, Fargate tasks need VPC endpoints (or NAT) to reach ECR and Secrets Manager. Also, security groups blocking outbound 443 would prevent API calls. The task EXECUTION role (not task role) handles image pulls and secret injection, so that distinction matters. Both networking issues (endpoints and SG rules) are the most common causes of these failures.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Organizations with multiple accounts. They want to share a centralized VPC (containing databases and shared services) with other accounts without VPC peering. Application teams in other accounts should deploy resources in the shared VPC subnets but should NOT be able to modify the VPC configuration. What is the correct approach?", opts:["Use AWS Resource Access Manager (RAM) to share specific subnets from the central VPC with participant accounts","Create VPC peering connections from each account to the central VPC","Deploy Transit Gateway and create route tables for each account","Replicate the shared services into each account's VPC using CloudFormation StackSets"], correct:0, exp:"AWS RAM allows sharing VPC subnets across accounts (VPC Sharing). Participant accounts can launch resources in shared subnets but cannot modify VPC configuration (routes, subnets, NACLs). No peering or Transit Gateway needed. This is simpler, more secure, and lower cost than alternatives.", domain:1},
  {q:"A global application uses Route 53 with latency-based routing. The security team requires that DNS queries for the application return ONLY healthy endpoints and that DNS responses are authenticated to prevent spoofing. Which combination of Route 53 features should be configured?", opts:["Latency-based routing with health checks and DNSSEC signing on the hosted zone","Latency-based routing with health checks and Route 53 Resolver with firewall rules","Geolocation routing with health checks and AWS Shield Advanced","Multivalue answer routing with health checks and Amazon Certificate Manager"], correct:0, exp:"Health checks ensure only healthy endpoints are returned. DNSSEC signing authenticates DNS responses cryptographically to prevent spoofing/cache poisoning. Latency-based routing was already specified. Route 53 supports DNSSEC for domain signing. Shield protects against DDoS, not DNS spoofing.", domain:1},
  {q:"An application team needs temporary AWS credentials to deploy resources from their CI/CD pipeline running on GitHub Actions. The credentials should not be long-lived and should follow the principle of least privilege. What is the MOST secure approach?", opts:["Create an IAM user with deployment permissions and store access keys in GitHub Secrets","Use GitHub Actions OIDC provider to assume an IAM role via web identity federation","Create a Lambda function that generates temporary credentials and call it from the pipeline","Use AWS SSO with a service account dedicated to the CI/CD pipeline"], correct:1, exp:"GitHub Actions OIDC (OpenID Connect) federation allows the pipeline to assume an IAM role without any stored long-term credentials. AWS verifies the OIDC token from GitHub and issues temporary STS credentials. This is zero-secret, auto-expiring, and scope-limited. IAM user access keys are long-lived secrets that can be leaked.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company runs a web application behind an ALB. They discover that a specific set of IP addresses from a foreign country is performing a credential stuffing attack. The security team wants to block these IPs immediately and also implement rate limiting for login attempts. Which combination provides the FASTEST and most effective protection?", opts:["Update the NACL of the ALB subnet to deny the IPs and implement application-level rate limiting","Attach AWS WAF to the ALB with an IP set rule to block the attackers and a rate-based rule for the login endpoint","Configure Security Groups on the ALB to deny the attacking IPs and enable AWS Shield Advanced","Use Route 53 geolocation routing to block the country and CloudFront with field-level encryption"], correct:1, exp:"AWS WAF on ALB provides immediate IP blocking via IP set rules and rate-based rules that can target specific URI paths (like /login). Changes propagate in seconds globally. NACLs can block IPs but don't support rate limiting. Security Groups only ALLOW (can't deny specific IPs). Route 53 geo-blocking is too broad.", domain:1},
  {q:"A healthcare company stores PHI (Protected Health Information) in an Aurora MySQL database. Compliance requires that the database is not accessible from the internet, all connections use TLS, data at rest is encrypted, and all database activity is logged for audit. Which combination of configurations ensures compliance?", opts:["Aurora in a private subnet, require_secure_transport parameter enabled, KMS encryption enabled, RDS Database Activity Streams enabled","Aurora in a private subnet, Security Group allowing port 3306 only from app subnet, SSE-S3 encryption, CloudWatch Logs for slow queries","Aurora in a public subnet with no public IP, Security Group restricting access, ACM certificates for TLS, CloudTrail for logging","Aurora with IAM authentication, VPN access only, default encryption, Performance Insights enabled"], correct:0, exp:"Private subnet ensures no internet access. require_secure_transport forces TLS for all connections. KMS encryption covers data at rest. Database Activity Streams provides comprehensive audit logging of all database activity (not just slow queries). CloudTrail logs API calls but not database queries.", domain:1},
  {q:"A solutions architect needs to allow an on-premises application to securely access AWS services (S3, DynamoDB) over a Direct Connect connection without the traffic going over the internet. The solution must use private IP addresses. Which Direct Connect configuration is required?", opts:["Public VIF (Virtual Interface) to access S3 and DynamoDB public endpoints","Private VIF to the VPC combined with VPC Gateway Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB","Transit VIF with a Transit Gateway and VPC endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB","Private VIF with a proxy EC2 instance that forwards requests to AWS services"], correct:1, exp:"Private VIF connects to the VPC over Direct Connect. VPC Gateway Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB allow access using private IPs within the VPC. Together, on-premises traffic flows: on-prem -> Direct Connect -> Private VIF -> VPC -> Gateway Endpoint -> S3/DynamoDB. All private, no internet. Public VIF would use public IPs.", domain:1},

  // DOMAIN 2: Design Resilient Architectures (~13 questions)
  {q:"A company runs a three-tier web application (ALB -> EC2 -> RDS). During a regional outage, the entire application was unavailable for 4 hours. Management requires a multi-region active-passive architecture with RTO of 30 minutes and RPO of 5 minutes. The database is the primary concern. Which architecture achieves this?", opts:["Aurora Global Database with a secondary region, Route 53 failover routing, and pre-provisioned infrastructure in the DR region (warm standby)","RDS Multi-AZ with automated backups, cross-region snapshot copy every 5 minutes, and CloudFormation in DR region","DynamoDB Global Tables with active-active configuration and Route 53 latency routing","Aurora with cross-region Read Replica, manual promotion during failover, and a pilot light setup in DR"], correct:0, exp:"Aurora Global Database provides <1 sec RPO (meets 5 min requirement), and promoting a secondary region takes ~1 minute. Warm standby with pre-provisioned infra and Route 53 failover achieves <30 min RTO. Snapshot copy every 5 min is not feasible and restore takes too long. Manual promotion fails the RTO. DynamoDB changes the database engine.", domain:2},
  {q:"A stateless API running on ECS Fargate behind an ALB experiences traffic spikes from 100 to 10,000 requests per second within 60 seconds. Users report HTTP 503 errors during scaling events because new tasks take 45 seconds to start and pass health checks. How should the architect solve this while maintaining cost efficiency?", opts:["Increase the minimum number of running tasks to handle the peak load","Configure Application Auto Scaling with a target tracking policy and reduce the health check grace period","Implement a scaling policy based on ALB request count, configure the deregistration delay to 45 seconds, and set the minimum healthy percent to 50%","Use a combination of scheduled scaling before predicted spikes, step scaling for unexpected spikes, and increase the desired count gradually using the warmup period"], correct:3, exp:"The core issue is tasks can't scale fast enough. Scheduled scaling pre-positions capacity for predicted spikes (cost-efficient vs over-provisioning). Step scaling with warmup periods prevents premature scaling decisions while new tasks start. This hybrid approach handles both predictable and unexpected traffic without maintaining peak capacity constantly.", domain:2},
  {q:"A media streaming company uses S3 to store video files and CloudFront for distribution. When a popular video goes viral, the origin S3 bucket receives too many requests, causing 503 SlowDown errors. The TTL is set to 24 hours so the content is cached, but initial requests to each edge location still hit the origin simultaneously. What is the BEST solution?", opts:["Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration to speed up origin requests","Increase the number of prefixes in S3 and distribute files across them","Enable CloudFront Origin Shield to reduce origin load by adding an additional caching layer","Pre-warm the CloudFront cache by making requests from each edge location before launch"], correct:2, exp:"Origin Shield adds a centralized caching layer between edge locations and the origin. When a viral video is requested from 400+ edge locations simultaneously, only Origin Shield (one layer) makes the request to S3, then serves all edge locations. This dramatically reduces origin load. Pre-warming is impractical for 400+ locations and not an AWS feature.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company processes financial transactions using a monolithic application on a single EC2 instance. The application writes to a local PostgreSQL database. They need to modernize for high availability with zero data loss, but the budget limits them to the minimum infrastructure needed. The application cannot be refactored immediately. What is the MOST cost-effective first step?", opts:["Migrate the database to Aurora PostgreSQL Multi-AZ and keep the application on EC2 in an Auto Scaling Group (min 1, max 1)","Migrate both application and database to Elastic Beanstalk with Multi-AZ RDS","Containerize the application on ECS Fargate with Aurora Serverless","Set up a second EC2 instance with synchronous database replication and a Route 53 failover record"], correct:0, exp:"Separating the database to Aurora PostgreSQL Multi-AZ provides zero data loss (synchronous replication) and automatic failover. ASG min/max 1 auto-replaces failed instances. This is the minimum cost approach that achieves HA for the data layer without refactoring the app. Aurora Multi-AZ is cheaper than running two EC2 instances with self-managed replication.", domain:2},
  {q:"An e-commerce application uses SQS to process orders. During Black Friday, the Dead Letter Queue (DLQ) received thousands of messages due to a downstream payment service outage that lasted 2 hours. The team wants to automatically reprocess DLQ messages once the payment service recovers, without manual intervention. What is the BEST approach?", opts:["Increase the maximum receive count (maxReceiveCount) and visibility timeout to allow more retries before messages go to the DLQ","Configure a CloudWatch alarm on the DLQ message count that triggers a Lambda function to move messages back to the main queue after verifying service health","Use SQS DLQ redrive (message move task) triggered by an EventBridge rule that detects when the payment service health check passes","Set up a scheduled Lambda that periodically checks the DLQ and redrives messages back to the source queue"], correct:2, exp:"SQS DLQ redrive (native message move task API) is the correct mechanism to move messages back to the source queue. Triggering it via EventBridge when the health check passes provides automatic recovery without manual intervention. The Lambda approach works but DLQ redrive is the native, less error-prone solution. Increasing retries just delays the problem.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company runs a data processing pipeline: S3 upload -> Lambda -> DynamoDB. During peak, Lambda sometimes exceeds the concurrency limit, causing invocations to be throttled and data to be lost. The processing order doesn't matter, but no data can be lost. Which architecture change ensures zero data loss with minimal modification?", opts:["Increase the Lambda reserved concurrency to match peak load","Add an SQS queue between S3 and Lambda, configure S3 event notifications to send to SQS, and set Lambda to poll the queue","Use S3 Event Notifications with SNS fanout to multiple Lambda functions to distribute load","Enable S3 Event Notifications with a destination on failure pointing to an SQS DLQ"], correct:1, exp:"SQS between S3 and Lambda provides a buffer. If Lambda is throttled, messages stay in the queue (up to 14 days) and are retried automatically. Lambda's SQS event source mapping handles polling and scaling. This ensures zero data loss. S3 event notifications directly to Lambda will drop events on throttle with only async retries (limited). The destination on failure only captures failures, not throttles.", domain:2},
  {q:"A microservices application uses multiple SQS queues and Lambda functions. The business requires that if any step in a multi-step order process fails (validate -> charge -> ship -> notify), the entire process should roll back (e.g., refund the charge if shipping fails). Which service orchestrates this pattern BEST?", opts:["SQS with a custom rollback queue that triggers compensating Lambda functions","AWS Step Functions with a Saga pattern using compensating transactions in Catch blocks","EventBridge with rules that trigger rollback Lambda functions on failure events","SNS fanout to all services simultaneously with a DynamoDB table tracking state"], correct:1, exp:"Step Functions with the Saga pattern is purpose-built for this. Each step has a compensating transaction defined in Catch/error blocks. If shipping fails, Step Functions automatically executes the refund (compensation for charge). This provides visual tracking, built-in retries, and guaranteed execution. Custom SQS rollback is complex and error-prone.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company has a legacy application that requires a file system shared across 50 EC2 instances in a single AZ. The application performs random I/O with millions of small files and requires sub-millisecond latency. EFS latency (3-5ms) is too slow. What storage solution meets these requirements?", opts:["Amazon FSx for Lustre linked to an S3 bucket","Amazon FSx for Windows File Server with SSD storage","Amazon EBS io2 with Multi-Attach enabled","Amazon FSx for NetApp ONTAP with SSD tier"], correct:0, exp:"FSx for Lustre provides sub-millisecond latency for millions of small file operations and supports hundreds of instances in parallel. It's designed for high-performance workloads. EBS Multi-Attach only supports up to 16 instances and requires cluster-aware filesystem. FSx for Windows uses SMB, not ideal for high-performance Linux workloads.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company deploys a new version of their application and discovers a critical bug 15 minutes after deployment. They need to roll back instantly. The application runs on EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling Group behind an ALB. Which deployment strategy would have allowed an instant rollback?", opts:["Rolling deployment with 25% batch size","Blue/Green deployment with Route 53 weighted routing at 100% to the new environment","In-place deployment with a pre-deployment AMI snapshot","Immutable deployment that replaces the Auto Scaling Group"], correct:1, exp:"Blue/Green keeps the old environment fully intact and running. Rollback is instant: just change Route 53 weight back to 100% old / 0% new. Takes seconds. Rolling deployment has already terminated old instances. In-place requires launching new instances from AMI. Immutable already replaced the ASG. Only Blue/Green has both environments live simultaneously.", domain:2},
  {q:"A global SaaS application needs to serve users in US, Europe, and Asia with the lowest possible latency for database reads. Writes happen primarily in the US. The application uses PostgreSQL and cannot switch to a different database engine. Users in Europe and Asia report read latency of 200ms+. What is the BEST architecture?", opts:["RDS PostgreSQL Multi-AZ in us-east-1 with Read Replicas in eu-west-1 and ap-southeast-1, Route 53 latency routing for reads","Aurora PostgreSQL Global Database with read-only secondary regions in Europe and Asia, application-level read routing","Aurora PostgreSQL with ProxySQL on EC2 in each region for connection pooling and read routing","Deploy separate RDS instances in each region with AWS DMS for continuous replication"], correct:1, exp:"Aurora Global Database with PostgreSQL replicates to secondary regions with <1 second lag and provides local read performance. It's purpose-built for this use case. RDS Read Replicas have higher replication lag (seconds) and less robust failover. DMS adds complexity and potential consistency issues. Aurora Global is the AWS-recommended approach for global PostgreSQL.", domain:2},
  {q:"An application uses an Auto Scaling Group with EC2 instances. After scaling out, new instances consistently fail health checks for 3 minutes before becoming healthy. During this period, the ASG launches additional unnecessary instances, causing cost spikes and oscillation. What combination of settings prevents this?", opts:["Increase the health check grace period to 4 minutes and set a cooldown period of 5 minutes","Set the health check grace period to 4 minutes, use target tracking scaling with a warmup period of 180 seconds, and enable instance warmup","Disable the ALB health check and rely only on EC2 status checks with a longer interval","Increase the minimum capacity to handle load without scaling and reduce maximum capacity"], correct:1, exp:"Health check grace period prevents the ASG from terminating instances during startup. Target tracking with warmup period tells the scaling algorithm to not count new instances' metrics until they're warm, preventing false scaling decisions. Together they eliminate oscillation. Cooldown alone doesn't account for warmup metrics. Disabling ALB health checks loses real health monitoring.", domain:2},
  {q:"A video processing application needs to transcode uploaded videos into multiple formats. Each transcode takes 20-45 minutes and is CPU-intensive. The application receives 0-100 videos per hour unpredictably. Videos must be processed within 2 hours of upload. What is the MOST cost-effective architecture?", opts:["Lambda functions triggered by S3 upload events for each transcode format","ECS Fargate tasks triggered by SQS messages from S3 event notifications, with task auto-scaling based on queue depth","EC2 Spot Instances in an Auto Scaling Group with SQS queue-based scaling","AWS Batch with Spot Instance compute environment and a job queue"], correct:3, exp:"AWS Batch with Spot Instances is purpose-built for batch processing. It automatically provisions optimal instance types, uses Spot (up to 90% savings), handles job queuing, retries on Spot interruption, and scales to zero when idle. Lambda can't run 20-45 min jobs (15 min limit). Fargate is more expensive than Spot. EC2 ASG with SQS works but requires more management than Batch.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company discovers that their RDS PostgreSQL database's storage will be full within 48 hours based on current growth. They cannot afford downtime. The current instance uses 10TB of gp2 storage. What is the FASTEST way to increase storage without downtime?", opts:["Create a Read Replica with larger storage, promote it, and redirect the application","Modify the RDS instance storage size directly (RDS supports dynamic storage scaling)","Enable RDS Storage Auto Scaling to automatically increase storage","Take a snapshot, restore to a larger instance, and switch DNS"], correct:2, exp:"RDS Storage Auto Scaling automatically increases storage when it detects free space is low (below 10%). Once enabled, it prevents the situation entirely. Direct modification also works without downtime but is manual and one-time. Storage Auto Scaling is the FASTEST because it can be enabled immediately and handles the growth automatically. Both B and C avoid downtime, but C is proactive.", domain:2},

  // DOMAIN 3: Design High-Performing Architectures (~12 questions)
  {q:"A company's DynamoDB table uses order_date as the partition key. Analytics queries need to retrieve all orders for a specific customer across all dates. The table has 500GB of data. Currently, this requires a full table scan. What is the MOST efficient solution?", opts:["Create a Global Secondary Index (GSI) with customer_id as the partition key and order_date as the sort key","Change the table's partition key to customer_id (requires table recreation)","Use a Scan operation with a FilterExpression on customer_id","Create a Local Secondary Index (LSI) with customer_id as the sort key"], correct:0, exp:"A GSI with customer_id as partition key enables efficient Query operations for all orders by a specific customer. The sort key of order_date allows range queries on dates. Scans read the entire 500GB table (expensive and slow). LSIs must use the same partition key as the table. Changing the partition key requires recreating the table and migrating data.", domain:3},
  {q:"An application uses API Gateway with Lambda backend. Under load testing, the API handles 5,000 requests/second but response times spike to 10+ seconds intermittently, while most responses return in 200ms. CloudWatch shows Lambda duration is consistently 200ms. What is the MOST likely cause and solution?", opts:["API Gateway throttling - increase the account-level throttle limit","Lambda cold starts - use Provisioned Concurrency to eliminate initialization time","Lambda concurrency limit - request a limit increase","API Gateway integration timeout - increase the timeout to 29 seconds"], correct:1, exp:"Consistent 200ms duration but intermittent 10+ second spikes is the classic cold start pattern. When Lambda scales up to handle concurrent requests, new execution environments need initialization (downloading code, running init). Provisioned Concurrency keeps environments warm, eliminating cold starts. Throttling would return 429 errors, not slow responses.", domain:3},
  {q:"A data analytics platform needs to process 10TB of CSV files in S3 using Athena. Queries currently take 20+ minutes and scan the full dataset. The data has columns: timestamp, region, user_id, event_type, and payload. Most queries filter by region and timestamp range. How should the data be optimized for Athena performance? (Choose the BEST combination)", opts:["Convert CSV to Parquet format, partition by region and date (year/month/day)","Add S3 Select to pre-filter data before Athena processes it","Create an AWS Glue ETL job to index the data and store results in RDS for querying","Keep CSV format but compress with GZIP and split into smaller files by region"], correct:0, exp:"Parquet is columnar (reads only needed columns, not entire rows - massive reduction for wide tables), supports predicate pushdown, and compresses well. Partitioning by region and date means Athena only scans relevant partitions (not 10TB). Together, this can reduce scan from 10TB to <100GB for typical queries. CSV with GZIP still scans all columns. S3 Select doesn't work with Athena.", domain:3},
  {q:"A real-time leaderboard application needs to rank millions of players by score with sub-millisecond latency. The leaderboard must support: get player rank, get top 100 players, and update scores. Which database and data structure combination is BEST?", opts:["DynamoDB with a GSI on score and a Query for top players","Amazon ElastiCache Redis with Sorted Sets (ZADD, ZRANK, ZRANGE)","Aurora MySQL with an indexed score column and LIMIT queries","DynamoDB with DAX caching and a scan operation for rankings"], correct:1, exp:"Redis Sorted Sets are purpose-built for leaderboards. ZADD updates scores in O(log N), ZRANK gets rank in O(log N), ZRANGE gets top-N in O(log N + M). All operations are sub-millisecond with millions of members. DynamoDB GSIs can't efficiently return rank position. SQL databases can't achieve sub-millisecond for millions of ranking operations.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company migrates a 50TB data warehouse from Oracle to AWS. The warehouse runs complex analytical queries joining 20+ tables, uses materialized views, and serves 200 concurrent BI users. Queries must complete within seconds. Which AWS service and configuration is MOST appropriate?", opts:["Amazon Athena with the data stored in Parquet on S3","Amazon Redshift RA3 nodes with concurrency scaling and materialized views","Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL with read replicas for BI users","Amazon RDS Oracle with the same schema on a large instance"], correct:1, exp:"Redshift RA3 is designed for petabyte-scale data warehouses with complex joins. It supports materialized views (familiar from Oracle), concurrency scaling auto-adds clusters for burst BI users (200+), and columnar storage delivers sub-second queries. Athena is for ad-hoc queries, not complex 20-table joins. Aurora is OLTP, not OLAP. RDS Oracle wastes the migration effort.", domain:3},
  {q:"A mobile application backend uses API Gateway -> Lambda -> DynamoDB. The app has a 'trending posts' feature that makes the same DynamoDB query 50,000 times per minute across all users. The data changes every 5 minutes. What is the MOST cost-effective way to reduce DynamoDB costs while maintaining performance?", opts:["Enable DAX in front of DynamoDB with a 5-minute TTL","Cache the trending posts response in API Gateway cache with a 5-minute TTL","Use Lambda environment variables to cache the query result with a 5-minute refresh","Store trending posts in ElastiCache Redis with a Lambda updating it every 5 minutes"], correct:1, exp:"API Gateway caching at the edge with 5-minute TTL eliminates ALL downstream calls (Lambda + DynamoDB) for the same request. 50,000 requests/min become ~1 request per 5 minutes to the backend. This saves both Lambda invocation costs AND DynamoDB read costs. DAX reduces DynamoDB reads but Lambda still executes 50,000 times. API GW cache is the cheapest layer to cache at.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company needs to migrate 100TB of data from on-premises to S3 within 2 weeks. Their internet connection is 1 Gbps (but only 60% available for the transfer). Direct Connect is not set up. What is the MOST reliable approach?", opts:["Use S3 Transfer Acceleration over the internet","Order an AWS Snowball Edge Storage Optimized device (80TB), transfer in two batches","Use multiple parallel uploads over the internet with multipart upload and retry logic","Set up AWS DataSync over the internet with bandwidth throttling"], correct:1, exp:"1 Gbps at 60% = ~600 Mbps = ~6.5TB/day = ~91TB in 14 days. This is barely enough and leaves no margin for errors/retries. Snowball Edge (80TB per device) provides reliable offline transfer unaffected by network issues. Order 2 devices (shipped in 1-2 days), load data in parallel, ship back. Total time well within 2 weeks. Transfer Acceleration and DataSync depend on the same constrained internet link.", domain:3},
  {q:"An application serves a mix of read-heavy and write-heavy workloads on Aurora MySQL. Read queries (analytics dashboards) are slowing down write transactions (order processing). The writes cannot tolerate any additional latency. How should the architect separate these workloads?", opts:["Add Aurora Read Replicas and direct analytics queries to the reader endpoint","Use Aurora parallel query to offload analytics to the storage layer","Create a custom endpoint for analytics that targets specific read replicas with a larger instance class","Use Aurora Global Database with the secondary region for analytics reads"], correct:2, exp:"Custom endpoints targeting dedicated read replicas with larger instance classes (optimized for analytics) provide the best isolation. The writer handles only transactions with no contention. Standard reader endpoint round-robins across all replicas including smaller ones. Parallel query helps with individual queries but doesn't isolate workloads. Global Database adds cross-region latency and cost for same-region analytics.", domain:3},
  {q:"A high-frequency trading platform needs to process market data with end-to-end latency under 10 milliseconds. The system receives 1 million messages per second from exchange feeds and must perform calculations and generate trade signals. Which architecture minimizes latency?", opts:["Kinesis Data Streams with Lambda consumers with provisioned concurrency","EC2 instances with enhanced networking (ENA) in a placement group, using kernel bypass with DPDK/ef_vi","API Gateway WebSocket with Lambda for real-time processing","Amazon MQ (ActiveMQ) with dedicated EC2 consumers"], correct:1, exp:"For <10ms end-to-end at 1M msg/sec, you need the lowest possible network latency. Placement groups provide single-digit microsecond latency between instances. Enhanced networking (ENA) with kernel bypass (DPDK) eliminates kernel network stack overhead. No managed service can achieve this latency requirement. Kinesis has ~200ms propagation delay. Lambda has cold starts. MQ adds broker latency.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company stores 1 billion objects in S3. They need to perform real-time SQL queries joining S3 data with data in an RDS PostgreSQL database. Queries should return results within 5 seconds. The S3 data is 20TB in Parquet format. What architecture achieves this?", opts:["Use Athena Federated Query with a PostgreSQL connector to join S3 and RDS data","Use Redshift Spectrum for S3 data with Redshift federated query to RDS for the join","Load all S3 data into RDS PostgreSQL for a single-database query","Use AWS Glue ETL to regularly materialize the join results into DynamoDB"], correct:1, exp:"Redshift Spectrum queries S3 data directly (Parquet is optimal) with Redshift's MPP engine for speed. Redshift federated query connects to RDS PostgreSQL. Together, they enable cross-source joins with Redshift's powerful query optimizer meeting the 5-second requirement. Athena Federated Query works but is slower for complex joins on 20TB. Loading 20TB into RDS is impractical.", domain:3},
  {q:"A social media application allows users to upload images that are then resized into 5 different dimensions. Currently, a single Lambda function receives the upload event and generates all 5 sizes sequentially (taking 25 seconds total). The user waits for all sizes to be ready. How should this be optimized for the FASTEST user experience?", opts:["Increase Lambda memory to get more CPU and process sizes in parallel threads","Use SNS to fan out the upload event to 5 separate Lambda functions, each generating one size, with a Step Functions workflow tracking completion","Trigger a Step Functions Parallel state that invokes 5 Lambda functions simultaneously and uses a callback when all complete","Use S3 Batch Operations to process all 5 sizes after upload"], correct:2, exp:"Step Functions Parallel state invokes all 5 Lambda functions concurrently (each takes ~5 seconds for one size). Total time drops from 25s to ~5s. The Parallel state automatically tracks completion of all branches and can notify when all 5 are done. SNS fan-out also parallelizes but lacks built-in completion tracking. Lambda threads work but share the same CPU allocation.", domain:3},
  {q:"A gaming company needs to match players in real-time with less than 100ms latency. The matchmaking considers player skill rating, geographic location, and ping time. Millions of players queue simultaneously during peak hours. Which architecture provides the lowest latency matchmaking?", opts:["DynamoDB with a GSI on skill rating and geographic queries with Lambda for matching logic","ElastiCache Redis with geospatial indexes (GEOADD/GEORADIUS) and sorted sets for skill rating, with a dedicated EC2 matching service","Amazon GameLift FlexMatch for matchmaking with custom rules","API Gateway WebSocket with Lambda for real-time communication and DynamoDB for player data"], correct:2, exp:"Amazon GameLift FlexMatch is purpose-built for game matchmaking. It supports custom rules (skill, latency, geography), handles millions of concurrent players, provides sub-100ms matching, and integrates with GameLift hosting. Building custom matchmaking with Redis works but requires significant engineering for edge cases (backfill, timeouts, fairness). FlexMatch handles all of this natively.", domain:3},

  // DOMAIN 4: Design Cost-Optimized Architectures (~10 questions)
  {q:"A company runs a web application on 20 m5.xlarge On-Demand instances 24/7. Traffic analysis shows: 10 instances are needed 24/7 (baseline), 5 more during business hours (12 hrs/day weekdays), and up to 20 during monthly sales events (4 days/month). Which purchasing combination minimizes cost?", opts:["20 Reserved Instances (1-year, All Upfront) for maximum discount","10 Reserved Instances (1-year) for baseline + On-Demand for the rest","10 Savings Plans (Compute) for baseline + 5 Scheduled Reserved Instances for business hours + Spot/On-Demand for sales events","10 Reserved Instances (3-year) for baseline + Auto Scaling with On-Demand for business hours + Spot Instances for sales event surplus"], correct:2, exp:"10 Compute Savings Plans cover the 24/7 baseline (up to 72% savings with flexibility). Scheduled Reserved Instances cover the predictable business-hours pattern cheaply. Sales event surplus uses Spot (90% savings) if fault-tolerant or On-Demand. 20 RIs wastes money on instances not needed 24/7. RIs + On-Demand misses savings on the predictable business-hours pattern.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company processes log files that arrive in S3. Files are analyzed heavily in the first 7 days, accessed occasionally for 30 days, rarely accessed for 90 days, and must be retained for 7 years for compliance. After 7 years, they can be deleted. Which S3 lifecycle configuration minimizes storage costs?", opts:["S3 Standard -> Standard-IA after 30 days -> Glacier Flexible Retrieval after 90 days -> Delete after 7 years","S3 Standard (7 days) -> Standard-IA (30 days) -> Glacier Instant Retrieval (90 days) -> Glacier Deep Archive (after 90 days) -> Delete after 7 years","S3 Intelligent-Tiering for the entire lifecycle with a 7-year expiration rule","S3 Standard (7 days) -> One Zone-IA (30 days) -> Glacier Flexible Retrieval (90 days) -> Glacier Deep Archive (after 120 days) -> Delete after 7 years"], correct:3, exp:"Compliance data that can't be lost rules out One Zone-IA... but wait - the logs CAN be regenerated from source systems (they're log files). One Zone-IA saves 20% vs Standard-IA for the occasionally-accessed period. Glacier Flexible for the rare-access period (retrieval in minutes-hours is fine for rare access). Deep Archive for the bulk of 7 years (cheapest, $1/TB/mo). This progression minimizes cost at each stage.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company runs a Spark-based ETL pipeline on Amazon EMR. The cluster runs 24/7 but is only actively processing data for 8 hours per day (3 batch jobs of varying length). The rest of the time it sits idle. The jobs can tolerate node failures and restarts. How should the architect reduce costs by at least 60%?", opts:["Use EMR with a mix of On-Demand master nodes and Spot Instance task nodes, and terminate the cluster between jobs using Step execution mode","Convert to AWS Glue ETL jobs that run only when needed (serverless)","Keep the cluster running 24/7 but use all Spot Instances","Use Reserved Instances for the entire cluster to get the RI discount"], correct:0, exp:"Step execution mode terminates the cluster after each step (no idle time = no idle cost). Spot task nodes provide 60-90% savings on compute. On-Demand master ensures cluster stability. This eliminates 16 hours of idle costs + Spot savings on active hours = easily >60% savings. Glue would require rewriting Spark code for Glue context. All-Spot risks losing the master. RIs for 8h/day utilization wastes money.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company has a development environment with 15 EC2 instances (various sizes), 3 RDS databases, and 5 ElastiCache clusters that are only used during business hours (8am-6pm, Monday-Friday). The current monthly cost is $12,000. What approach provides the GREATEST cost savings?", opts:["Purchase Reserved Instances for all resources at the 1-year term","Use AWS Instance Scheduler to automatically stop/start EC2 and RDS instances on a schedule, and implement ElastiCache backup/restore for the clusters","Migrate all workloads to Lambda and DynamoDB on-demand for a serverless architecture","Right-size all instances to one size smaller based on CPU utilization data"], correct:1, exp:"Business hours M-F = 50 hours/week out of 168 = ~30% utilization. Stopping instances during off-hours saves ~70% (from $12K to ~$3.6K). Instance Scheduler is an AWS solution that automates this. RIs would save ~40% but you still pay for idle time. Serverless migration requires re-architecture effort. Right-sizing might save 20-30% but instances still run idle.", domain:4},
  {q:"A machine learning team runs training jobs that take 4-12 hours on p3.8xlarge instances ($24.48/hr On-Demand). Jobs can checkpoint progress every 30 minutes to S3 and resume from the last checkpoint if interrupted. They run approximately 20 jobs per month. How should the architect minimize training costs?", opts:["Use Spot Instances with checkpointing and automatic resume via CloudWatch Events and Lambda on spot interruption","Purchase a 1-year Reserved Instance for p3.8xlarge","Use On-Demand instances but stop them manually during off-hours","Use SageMaker Managed Spot Training with checkpointing enabled"], correct:3, exp:"SageMaker Managed Spot Training handles everything: uses Spot Instances (70-90% savings), automatically checkpoints, automatically resumes from checkpoint on interruption, and manages the infrastructure. For ML training specifically, this is simpler than building custom Spot interruption handling with CloudWatch+Lambda. Cost reduction: ~$24.48 * 8hr * 20 jobs = ~$3,917/mo On-Demand vs ~$1,175/mo with Spot = 70% savings.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company hosts a multi-tier application with the following monthly AWS costs: EC2 ($15,000), RDS ($8,000), Data Transfer ($5,000), NAT Gateway ($3,000), CloudWatch ($2,000). Total: $33,000/month. Which TWO changes would provide the LARGEST cost reduction?", opts:["Move to Graviton instances (EC2) and enable RDS Reserved Instances (1-year All Upfront)","Use VPC endpoints to reduce NAT Gateway data processing and enable CloudWatch Logs Insights instead of custom metrics","Consolidate to fewer, larger EC2 instances and enable S3 Transfer Acceleration","Reduce CloudWatch log retention to 7 days and use smaller RDS instance types"], correct:0, exp:"EC2 is the largest cost ($15K). Graviton (ARM) instances are 20-40% cheaper with often better performance. That's $3K-6K savings. RDS is second largest ($8K). 1-year All Upfront RI saves ~40% = $3.2K. Combined savings: $6.2K-9.2K/month. VPC endpoints save on NAT ($3K) but it's a smaller absolute number. CloudWatch is only $2K. Always target the largest cost categories first for maximum impact.", domain:4},
  {q:"A startup runs a SaaS application that currently costs $5,000/month on AWS. They expect 10x user growth in 12 months but want costs to grow no more than 3x. The application uses EC2 (40% of cost), RDS (30%), and data transfer (30%). Which architectural changes best achieve sub-linear cost scaling?", opts:["Migrate EC2 to Lambda (pay-per-request) and RDS to DynamoDB on-demand (pay-per-request) to align costs with actual usage","Add CloudFront for static content delivery (reduces data transfer), implement ElastiCache (reduces database load), and use Auto Scaling with mixed instances (Spot + On-Demand)","Purchase 3-year Reserved Instances for EC2 and RDS to lock in current pricing","Migrate to a single large EC2 instance to reduce per-instance overhead"], correct:1, exp:"CloudFront reduces origin data transfer by 60-80% (caching at edge), addressing the 30% data transfer cost that would 10x. ElastiCache absorbs 80%+ of read traffic, meaning RDS doesn't need to scale linearly with users. Auto Scaling with Spot handles compute spikes efficiently. Together, costs scale ~2-3x for 10x users. Lambda+DynamoDB might achieve this but requires complete re-architecture. RIs don't help with growth.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company runs a CI/CD pipeline that provisions full AWS environments for each pull request (EC2, RDS, ElastiCache) for testing. Each environment costs $15/hour and there are ~50 PRs per day, each running for 3 hours average. Monthly testing infrastructure cost is approximately $67,500. How should costs be reduced while maintaining test quality?", opts:["Use smaller instance types for all test resources","Share a single test environment across all PRs using feature flags","Use LocalStack or containers for unit/integration tests, and only provision full AWS environments for critical integration tests on merge to main","Limit PR environments to only run during business hours"], correct:2, exp:"Most PR tests don't need full AWS environments. LocalStack/containers can run most tests locally or in CI (near-zero cost). Only provision real AWS resources for final integration/staging tests before merge. If only 10% of tests need real AWS: $67,500 * 10% = $6,750/month (90% reduction). Smaller instances might save 30-50%. Shared environments have test isolation issues. Business-hours-only saves ~30%.", domain:4},
  {q:"A data lake on S3 grows by 5TB per month. Data is written once and read frequently in the first week, then very rarely. The company currently uses S3 Standard for everything and monthly storage costs are $25,000 for 500TB. They don't know which specific objects will be accessed after the first week. What approach minimizes costs with ZERO risk of access delays?", opts:["S3 Intelligent-Tiering for all objects","S3 Standard with lifecycle to Standard-IA after 7 days","S3 Standard with lifecycle to Glacier Instant Retrieval after 7 days","S3 Standard with lifecycle to One Zone-IA after 7 days"], correct:0, exp:"S3 Intelligent-Tiering automatically moves objects between access tiers with ZERO retrieval fees and no performance impact (instant access in all tiers). Since they don't know which objects are accessed (can't predict), IT is ideal - it monitors per-object access patterns. IA charges retrieval fees when rare objects ARE accessed. Glacier Instant has higher retrieval cost. One Zone-IA risks data loss. IT monitoring fee ($0.0025/1000 objects) is trivial vs the savings on 500TB.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company has 200 AWS accounts under Organizations. They want to identify unused resources (unattached EBS volumes, idle EC2, unused Elastic IPs, oversized instances) across ALL accounts and get actionable recommendations. Which combination provides the MOST comprehensive cost optimization visibility?", opts:["AWS Cost Explorer with rightsizing recommendations in each account","AWS Trusted Advisor (Business/Enterprise support) with organizational view and AWS Compute Optimizer","Custom Lambda functions scanning each account via cross-account roles and storing findings in a central DynamoDB table","AWS Config rules for unused resources with SNS notifications to a central account"], correct:1, exp:"Trusted Advisor organizational view surfaces idle/underutilized resources across all 200 accounts centrally (unattached EBS, idle EC2, unused EIPs). Compute Optimizer provides specific rightsizing recommendations with predicted performance impact. Together they cover detection AND actionable recommendations. Cost Explorer rightsizing only works per-account. Custom Lambda is heavy engineering for a solved problem.", domain:4}
]
